Behavioral questions

Why Facebook?

What is an interesting technical thing that you learn this past year?

What is the most technically challenging problem you solved in the last year?

What you can improve on if you went back?

Empathy and self-awareness questions

Most frequent

Tell me about a time you had a conflict with someone. How did you solve it?

Tell me about a time you received negative feedback. (Prepare at least 2 examples)

Other Versions

How do you like to give and receive feedback?

How do you deal with differences of opinion when working on a team?

Tell me about a time where you and your co-worker disagreed about a technical decision

What were some excellent collaborations you've had?

Facebook “Perks”
Please don’t ask about these things when a Facebook interview asks you questions because you’ll already know it from here! You can mention them as if you know them though!

Hackamonths

For engineers that have been at the company for more than a year, they can spend an entire month working for another team. There’s a website where teams post “hack-a-months” and engineers can choose to take on that hack-a-month with another team for an entire month. 

Facebook is incredibly encouraging of team mobility and doing a hack-a-month is a good way for engineers to both explore other teams and do a trial to see if there is a mutual fit between the hack-a-monther and the new team.

Bootcamp

This and hack-a-month’s are the more unique parts of Facebook’s culture. Bootcamp is a 6 - 12 week (sometimes more) process where a new Facebook engineer learns the technologies specific to Facebook through a series of classes and small but real engineering tasks. It’s also a time for new engineers to try out different teams they are interested in. Unlike most new grad engineer positions, at Facebook you get to choose what team you want to work for as a bootcamper. 
